Trinidad and Tobago were not exclusively Spanish but were under Spanish rule from 1498 to 1797, however a part of it was
Anguilla briefly from 1650 to 1655 and again in 1680 then it returned to British control
Aruba briefly from 1513 until the Dutch captured it in 1636
Bonaire also briefly under Spanish rule from 1499 until the Dutch took it over in 1636
Curaçao which was ruled by Spain from 1499 but was later taken over by the Dutch West India Company in 1634
Dominica was visited and claimed by Spain but remained a French colony
Grenada also briefly under Spanish rule before becoming a French colony then ceded to Britain

Martinique had been sighted by Christopher Columbus on his fourth voyage, however no settlement attempt was made by Spain as it was already settled by the indigenous Arawak people which were encountered by French colonizers in 1635 and established a settlement in 1636 then captured by the British but returned to France with the signing of the Treaty of Paris

Saint Croix had been sighted by Christopher Columbus on his second voyage however no permanent Spanish settlement was made, it was later sold from the French West India Company to the Danish West India Company in 1733
Saint John and Saint Thomas were part of the Danish West India Company in 1672 but previously had been settled briefly by the English who fought off a Spanish attack
Saba also had brief periods under Spanish rule between 1519 until it was taken over by the Dutch
Saint Eustatius also captured from Spain then later changed hands multiple times with other nations including France and the Netherlands

Saint Kitts was visited and claimed by Christopher Columbus for Spain but no settlement attempt was made due to hostility from the Kalinago people which were encountered by British colonizers in 1624 and established a settlement however it would be shared between England and France until being ceded to Britain with the signing of the Treaty of Utrecht

Saint Lucia had been claimed by Spain, later settled by the French who defended against attacks by the British, then captured by the British but returned multiple times to different nations ultimately becoming part of the United Kingdom in 1814

Sint Maarten which was divided between France and the Netherlands with no record that it was previously under Spanish rule however this area is a very narrow island sharing bordering with French Saint-Martin
Tortuga was settled by Spain then later taken over by French buccaneers
